<subSubSection lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="21" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,661,767]" box="[151,281,661,687]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Etymology</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,661,767]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
The specific epithet is a reference to the difficulty in recognizing the species, mainly in distinguishing it from 
<taxonomicName authority="Lopes-Andrade, 2008" authorityName="Lopes-Andrade" authorityYear="2008" box="[215,399,741,766]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouchardi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[215,399,741,766]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Scol. bouchardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[407,500,741,767]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[407,500,741,767]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,821,967]" box="[151,268,821,847]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,821,967]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
The species belongs to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lopes-Andrade" authorityYear="2008" box="[519,638,861,886]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouchardi">
<emphasis box="[519,638,861,886]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">bouchardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group, so it differs from the other 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Blair" authorityYear="1928" box="[1146,1265,861,886]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1146,1265,861,886]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Scolytocis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
mainly by the triconcave prosternum. It differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Lopes-Andrade, 2008" authorityName="Lopes-Andrade" authorityYear="2008" box="[604,789,901,926]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouchardi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[604,789,901,926]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Scol. bouchardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[797,892,901,927]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[797,892,901,927]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, the most closely related species, by the comparatively smaller body (total length less than 
<quantity box="[693,784,941,967]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
) and small eyes (1.0X the basal width of scutellum).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,1021,1847]" box="[151,288,1021,1047]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,1021,1847]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis box="[198,313,1061,1086]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<typeStatus box="[198,309,1061,1086]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Holotype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[329,471,1061,1087]" captionStart="FIGURES 36–38" captionStartId="63.[151,269,1835,1859]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1811]" captionTargetId="figure-31@63.[151,1436,194,1811]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 36–38. Scolytocis difficillimus sp. nov, holotype. 36. Dorsal view. 37. Lateral view. 38. Ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127007" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127007/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs. 36–38</figureCitation>
) Measurements in mm: TL 1.16; PL 0.42; PW 0.53; EL 0.74; EW 0.53; GD 0.53. Ratios: PL/PW 0.80; EL/EW 1.40; EL/PL 1.75; GD/EW 1.00; TL/EW 2.20. Body dark brown; antennae, mouthparts and legs yellowish brown. Head with shallow, sparse, inconspicuous punctation; interstice between punctures finely microreticulate. Each antenna (
<figureCitation box="[842,955,1181,1207]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–65" captionStartId="72.[151,269,1404,1428]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-85@72.[151,1436,194,1381]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 63–65. Antennae of the Northern Neotropical Scolytocis Blair. 63. Scol. bouchardi sp. nov. (A), Scol. cariborum sp. nov. (B), Scol. danielssoni sp. nov. (C). 64. Scol. difficillimus sp. nov. (A), Scol. howdeni sp. nov. (B), Scol. indecisus sp. nov. (C). 65. Scol. kiskeyensis sp. nov. (A), Scol. lawrencei sp. nov. (B), Scol. panamensis sp. nov. (C). First antennomere not shown in Scol. danielssoni sp. nov. (63C, asterisk)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127031" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127031/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 64A</figureCitation>
, 
<typeStatus box="[970,1073,1181,1207]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">paratype</typeStatus>
) with nine antennomeres (FL 
<quantity box="[151,266,1221,1247]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.8" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="0.078">0.078mm</quantity>
; CL 
<quantity box="[326,441,1221,1247]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="0.15">0.150mm</quantity>
; CL/FL 1.94); length of the antennomeres (in mm) as follows: 0.088; 0.040; 0.040; 0.013; 0.013; 0.013; 0.040; 0.038; 0.073. Eyes with greatest width 1.0X the basal width of scutellum. Pronotal punctation coarse, sparse, shallow; punctures separated by a distance of two to four punctures widths; interstice microreticulate; anterolateral margins slightly arched inwards; posterolateral angles broadly rounded; posterior margin without rugose border. Scutellum with some fine, sparse punctures; basal width 0.21X the EW. Elytral punctation confuse at base and subseriate at disc; punctures coarse, shallow, irregular; punctures without conspicuous border; interstice between punctures finely rugose; elytral apex subacute, declivity with weak concavity; cuticular globules very small, inconspicuous; elytral suture weakly margined at apical third. Each hindwing (
<figureCitation box="[343,427,1541,1567]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–59" captionStartId="70.[151,269,1269,1293]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1245]" captionTargetId="figure-39@70.[151,1436,194,1245]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="FIGURES 57–59. Hindwings of Northern Neotropical Scolytocis Blair. 57. Scol. difficillimus sp. nov. 58. Scol. howdeni sp. nov. 59. Scol. indecisus sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127023" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127023/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
) with apical area bearing one vague, incomplete pigmented line near the anterior margin. Prosternum triconcave, without longitudinal carina at midline; surface shiny, rugose. Metaventrite bearing small and sparse setae, with interstice finely microreticulate; discrimen one-fifth the length of the metaventrite at midline. Abdominal ventrites bearing small and sparse setae; interstice finely microreticulate. Each metatibiae (
<figureCitation box="[357,464,1701,1727]" captionStart="FIGURES 66–68" captionStartId="73.[151,269,1404,1428]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-72@73.[151,1436,194,1381]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="FIGURES 66–68. Metatibiae of the Northern Neotropical Scolytocis Blair. 66. Scol. bouchardi sp. nov. (A), Scol. cariborum sp. nov. (B), Scol. danielssoni sp. nov. (C). 67. Scol. difficillimus sp. nov. (A), Scol. howdeni sp. nov. (B), Scol. indecisus sp. nov. (C). 68. Scol. kiskeyensis sp. nov. (A), Scol. lawrencei sp. nov. (B), Scol. panamensis sp. nov. (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127033" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127033/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 67A</figureCitation>
) broadly rounded, near 3.5X as long as broad; outer edge with spines (around 20) regularly distributed at apical two thirds and then getting sparser. 
<emphasis box="[947,1321,1741,1766]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Male genitalia (in a 
<typeStatus box="[1199,1308,1741,1766]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">paratype</typeStatus>
).
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1339,1426,1741,1767]" captionStart="FIGURES 69–71" captionStartId="74.[151,269,1427,1451]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1403]" captionTargetId="figure-57@74.[151,1436,194,1403]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="FIGURES 69–71. Male genitalia of Scolytocis Blair showing the Y-shaped ninth segment (ix), basal piece (b.p), tegmen (teg) and penis (pen). 69. Scol. bouchardi sp. nov. 70. Scol. cariborum sp. nov. (ninth segment broken; see asterisks). 71. Scol. difficillimus sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127037" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127037/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 71</figureCitation>
) Apex of tegmen (sclerotized apical two-thirds) subtriangular; median lobe not observed, probably extremely membranous.
</paragraph>
