<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,810,1076]" box="[151,278,810,836]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Comments</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,810,1076]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
I was a little bit reluctant in describing this species, due to its similarities to 
<taxonomicName authority="Lopes-Andrade, 2008" authorityName="Lopes-Andrade" authorityYear="2008" box="[1079,1262,850,875]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouchardi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1079,1262,850,875]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Scol. bouchardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1269,1362,850,876]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1269,1362,850,876]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
However, after a careful comparison of morphological features, I concluded that some specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[1332,1431,890,916]" name="Ecuador" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, from a single field collection, are quite distinct and cannot be adequately included in any of the new northern Neotropical species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Blair" authorityYear="1928" box="[418,537,970,995]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[418,537,970,995]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Scolytocis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. After delimiting 
<taxonomicName authority="Lopes-Andrade, 2008" authorityName="Lopes-Andrade" authorityYear="2008" box="[746,951,970,995]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="difficillimus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[746,951,970,995]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Scol. difficillimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[957,1050,970,996]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[957,1050,970,996]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, I found out that it was very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Lopes-Andrade, 2008" authorityName="Lopes-Andrade" authorityYear="2008" box="[226,410,1010,1035]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouchardi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[226,410,1010,1035]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Scol. bouchardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[417,510,1010,1036]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[417,510,1010,1036]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in the morphology of hindwings, tibiae, and prosternum (“triconcave”), which led me to define a morphological group for both species (the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lopes-Andrade" authorityYear="2008" box="[868,987,1050,1075]" class="Insecta" family="Ciidae" genus="Scolytocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouchardi">
<emphasis box="[868,987,1050,1075]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">bouchardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group).
</paragraph>
